		<description>@Johannes: Thanks, I wasn&#039;t aware of LID. I believe XDI may have a similar idea in having i-name number, a permanent your only identifier and i-name name, which can be transferred, that points to the number.

I don&#039;t think cost per time prevents identifier hoarding and I&#039;m also sceptical that XRI&#039;s flexibility will do it. I&#039;m doubtful that problem is reall solvable until namescape is not more or less uniformaly (un)appealing.

@Tara: You don&#039;t really need to do this. You can use client&#039;s URL as their OpenID and delegate real authentication to whichever provider you best like (at the moment). True, people are still free to do create OpenIDs with your name on other providers, but the same is true for email right now as well.</description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>@Johannes: Thanks, I wasn&#8217;t aware of LID. I believe XDI may have a similar idea in having i-name number, a permanent your only identifier and i-name name, which can be transferred, that points to the number.</p>
<p>I don&#8217;t think cost per time prevents identifier hoarding and I&#8217;m also sceptical that XRI&#8217;s flexibility will do it. I&#8217;m doubtful that problem is reall solvable until namescape is not more or less uniformaly (un)appealing.</p>
<p>@Tara: You don&#8217;t really need to do this. You can use client&#8217;s URL as their OpenID and delegate real authentication to whichever provider you best like (at the moment). True, people are still free to do create OpenIDs with your name on other providers, but the same is true for email right now as well.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
