		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://markos.gaivo.net/blog/?p=223#comment-44977</guid>
		<description>OpenID hoarding is an interesting problem. I don&#039;t actually use OpenID, but the idea that someone else might use my name in their identifier doesn&#039;t thrill me. I can see how this would lead to a proliferation of sign-up-just-to-get-the-name.

I work in web development, every time a client wants to start an online business, I make sure they get all the domains plus the standard company@gmail, hotmail, yahoo etc.

Now we need to add OpenID identifiers to that list too.</description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>OpenID hoarding is an interesting problem. I don&#8217;t actually use OpenID, but the idea that someone else might use my name in their identifier doesn&#8217;t thrill me. I can see how this would lead to a proliferation of sign-up-just-to-get-the-name.</p>
<p>I work in web development, every time a client wants to start an online business, I make sure they get all the domains plus the standard company@gmail, hotmail, yahoo etc.</p>
<p>Now we need to add OpenID identifiers to that list too.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
	</item>
	<item>
		<title>By: Johannes Ernst</title>
		<link>http://markos.gaivo.net/blog/?p=223&#038;cpage=1#comment-44966</link>
		<dc:creator>Johannes Ernst</dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sun, 15 Apr 2007 20:27:29 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://markos.gaivo.net/blog/?p=223#comment-44966</guid>
		<description>I would think that unless identifiers have a cost per time associated with it (as it is for DNS domains), it would lead to extreme identifier hoarding, and thus a system built on such identifiers would be infeasible in practice because all &quot;good&quot; identifiers would be owned and unused. (Unless identifiers were non-human-readable, which would have other problems). That would apply to all identifier-based systems (OpenID URLs, XRI/i-names and all current and future alternatives.)

In the longer term, I think people will get around to the idea we pioneered in &lt;a href=&quot;http://lid.netmesh.org/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;LID&lt;/a&gt; to associate a public key with each identifier which could be taken to a new identifier. That public key could be your less fleeting identifier.</description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I would think that unless identifiers have a cost per time associated with it (as it is for DNS domains), it would lead to extreme identifier hoarding, and thus a system built on such identifiers would be infeasible in practice because all &#8220;good&#8221; identifiers would be owned and unused. (Unless identifiers were non-human-readable, which would have other problems). That would apply to all identifier-based systems (OpenID URLs, XRI/i-names and all current and future alternatives.)</p>
<p>In the longer term, I think people will get around to the idea we pioneered in <a href="http://lid.netmesh.org/">LID</a> to associate a public key with each identifier which could be taken to a new identifier. That public key could be your less fleeting identifier.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
